**Code Explanation:**

The code performs the effective fractional operator derivation for the Sisyphus cooling datasets. It follows these steps: 1. Momentum Estimation: It estimates the momentum p and its increment dp using finite differences from the position trajectories (p = dx/dt, dp = p(t+dt) - p(t)), given the discrete time step dt = 0.1. 2. Drift and Diffusion Estimation: It bins the momentum values to compute the empirical local drift A(p) = <dp> / dt and diffusion B(p) = Var(dp) / (2dt). These are plotted against the theoretical functions A(p) = -gamma0 * p / (1 + (p/p0)^2) and B(p) = sigma^2 / 2. 3. Spatial Dependence: To determine if the effective fractional operator is spatially dependent, it projects the noise back into position space by binning the position x and computing the variance of dx conditional on x. A low coefficient of variation (CV) across the bins indicates that the effective noise is spatially homogeneous (independent of x). 4. Theoretical vs Empirical alpha: It calculates the theoretical Tsallis q-index for the momentum distribution (q = 1 + sigma^2/gamma0) and the corresponding theoretical Levy tail index alpha = (3-q)/(q-1). These values are printed alongside the empirical q-index (from Step 3) and the empirical tail alpha (from Step 1) to link the microscopic friction parameters to the macroscopic fractional operator.

